1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,060
Welcome to this new in-depth study; today we explore one of the most complex dynamics

2
00:00:05,060 --> 00:00:06,060
of our time.

3
00:00:06,060 --> 00:00:10,580
And the exact title of our analysis is precisely this: why aging slows down

4
00:00:10,580 --> 00:00:11,580
GDP.

5
00:00:11,580 --> 00:00:15,179
We are going to deconstruct a fascinating piece of macroeconomic research published in the American

6
00:00:15,179 --> 00:00:19,620
Economic Journal, to understand exactly how major demographic changes are

7
00:00:19,620 --> 00:00:22,379
already rewriting the rules of global economic growth.

8
00:00:22,379 --> 00:00:26,460
Now, let's stop for a moment, because there is a massive myth to debunk.

9
00:00:26,460 --> 00:00:30,900
When we think of an aging population, a scene immediately comes to mind.

10
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:36,579
People who retire, stop working, and consequently the economy shrinks.

11
00:00:36,579 --> 00:00:39,380
It seems like the most logical explanation in the world, doesn't it?

12
00:00:39,380 --> 00:00:44,140
But the data tells us something very different, and decidedly more surprising.

13
00:00:44,140 --> 00:00:49,100
Aging reduces collective wealth, certainly, but the real reasons go far

14
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:52,219
beyond a simple decrease in the number of workers.

15
00:00:52,460 --> 00:00:55,019
So, here is our map for today.

16
00:00:55,019 --> 00:01:00,780
We will start by looking at the global demographic phenomenon, then address the problem of causality

17
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:02,700
and the real numbers of the decline.

18
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:07,659
We will ask ourselves if the problem is fewer workers or lower productivity, we will analyze

19
00:01:07,659 --> 00:01:12,500
the effect on new generations and, finally, we will outline the prospects for the future.

20
00:01:12,500 --> 00:01:13,500
Let's begin!

21
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:20,060
Section 1, a global demographic phenomenon, a truly epochal trend.

22
00:01:20,140 --> 00:01:24,379
To understand the scope of all this, we must look at recent history.

23
00:01:24,379 --> 00:01:29,579
The populations of developed countries have never been this old, ever.

24
00:01:29,579 --> 00:01:34,460
If we take the United States as a laboratory, we see that in the 80s there was a very strong

25
00:01:34,460 --> 00:01:37,540
aging process, especially in the western states.

26
00:01:37,540 --> 00:01:43,659
Then, between the 90s and 2000, a sort of pause, a temporary slowdown, due to the fact

27
00:01:43,659 --> 00:01:47,980
that the massive baby boomer generation was in the prime of their working adulthood.

28
00:01:48,020 --> 00:01:53,540
But from 2000 onwards, aging started to race again with massive acceleration everywhere.

29
00:01:53,540 --> 00:01:56,420
And this brings us to a sobering statistic.

30
00:01:56,420 --> 00:02:02,460
Between 1980 and 2010, the share of the American population over 60 years old

31
00:02:02,460 --> 00:02:06,100
jumped forward by 16.8%.

32
00:02:06,100 --> 00:02:10,379
It is an epochal demographic change, and from a research point of view,

33
00:02:10,379 --> 00:02:14,860
it provides the perfect data pool to understand what really happens to an economy

34
00:02:14,860 --> 00:02:17,900
when white hair becomes the majority.

35
00:02:17,900 --> 00:02:22,020
Moving on to Section 2, the problem of causality.

36
00:02:22,020 --> 00:02:25,780
Or rather, are we looking at the cause or the effect?

37
00:02:25,780 --> 00:02:31,780
Here we get to the heart of it because measuring demographic impact is a real nightmare for economists.

38
00:02:31,780 --> 00:02:34,260
Imagine a city with a broken economy.

39
00:02:34,260 --> 00:02:37,460
Young people pack their bags and go elsewhere to look for work,

40
00:02:37,460 --> 00:02:41,420
leaving behind a chronologically much older population.

41
00:02:41,460 --> 00:02:45,660
In this case, it is the economic crisis that causes the local aging,

42
00:02:45,660 --> 00:02:48,300
but what happens if the opposite were true?

43
00:02:48,300 --> 00:02:53,700
What if it were precisely the presence of an elderly population causing the stagnation of the economy?

44
00:02:53,700 --> 00:02:59,380
Untangling this chicken-and-egg dilemma is literally fundamental.

45
00:02:59,380 --> 00:03:02,580
So, how did researchers solve this problem?

46
00:03:02,580 --> 00:03:06,180
They invented a sort of statistical time machine.

47
00:03:06,180 --> 00:03:10,420
They took the demographic structure from 10, 20, or even 40 years ago

48
00:03:10,420 --> 00:03:13,860
and applied national survival rates to it,

49
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:15,660
a brilliant mathematical trick

50
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:17,540
that allows for the calculation of aging

51
00:03:17,540 --> 00:03:21,260
based exclusively on historical birth and mortality data.

52
00:03:21,260 --> 00:03:24,660
In this way, they completely eliminated the noise caused by young people

53
00:03:24,660 --> 00:03:26,580
emigrating for economic reasons,

54
00:03:26,580 --> 00:03:29,220
pure data ready to be analyzed.

55
00:03:29,220 --> 00:03:33,300
And this brings us to Section 3, the numbers of the decline.

56
00:03:33,300 --> 00:03:35,540
What is the real impact on GDP?

57
00:03:35,540 --> 00:03:36,980
Now that the data is clean,

58
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:39,540
the final result is astounding.

59
00:03:39,579 --> 00:03:42,179
The crucial point of the whole analysis is this.

60
00:03:42,179 --> 00:03:46,099
A 10% increase in the share of the population over sixty

61
00:03:46,099 --> 00:03:50,819
causes a massive 5.5% drop in GDP per capita.

62
00:03:50,819 --> 00:03:53,299
We are not talking about a slight slowdown.

63
00:03:53,299 --> 00:03:55,780
We are talking about a macroeconomic blow

64
00:03:55,780 --> 00:03:59,699
that directly burns away the wealth generated for every single citizen.

65
00:03:59,699 --> 00:04:02,859
To give an idea of what this means in practice,

66
00:04:02,859 --> 00:04:05,620
the researchers spread it out on an annual basis.

67
00:04:05,620 --> 00:04:07,060
This demographic change

68
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:11,939
stole 1.03% of growth from the economic development of the United States,

69
00:04:11,939 --> 00:04:13,659
every single year.

70
00:04:13,659 --> 00:04:17,540
For 30 years in a row, from 1980 to 2010,

71
00:04:17,540 --> 00:04:22,019
exactly like driving for decades with the handbrake constantly engaged.

72
00:04:22,019 --> 00:04:23,420
Section 4.

73
00:04:23,420 --> 00:04:26,620
Fewer workers or lower productivity.

74
00:04:26,620 --> 00:04:29,340
Let's break down this decline.

75
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:31,939
And here is the million-dollar question,

76
00:04:31,939 --> 00:04:33,340
why it happens.

77
00:04:33,340 --> 00:04:35,540
The answer is undoubtedly the discovery

78
00:04:35,540 --> 00:04:37,700
most unexpected of the entire study.

79
00:04:37,700 --> 00:04:39,060
Looking at this graph,

80
00:04:39,060 --> 00:04:42,620
one notices that only 33% of the total economic damage

81
00:04:42,620 --> 00:04:44,580
comes from the drop in employment,

82
00:04:44,580 --> 00:04:47,900
that is, from the physiological fact that there are more retirees.

83
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:50,860
But the remaining 67%

84
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:53,700
comes from a collapse in productivity.

85
00:04:53,700 --> 00:04:56,820
So the problem is not just having fewer people working.

86
00:04:56,820 --> 00:05:01,939
The real drama is that the system itself makes those who work much, much less productive.

87
00:05:01,939 --> 00:05:04,860
The exact words used in the scientific paper

88
00:05:04,900 --> 00:05:06,500
hit the mark.

89
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:10,620
Two-thirds of the reduction are due to slower growth

90
00:05:10,620 --> 00:05:12,819
of labor productivity.

91
00:05:12,819 --> 00:05:16,860
An aging country is not just shrinking numerically,

92
00:05:16,860 --> 00:05:19,860
it is literally shifting into a lower gear

93
00:05:19,860 --> 00:05:22,620
in the efficiency of its entire economy.

94
00:05:22,620 --> 00:05:24,259
Let's move to Section 5,

95
00:05:24,259 --> 00:05:26,340
the effect on new generations,

96
00:05:26,340 --> 00:05:29,020
so-called negative spillovers.

97
00:05:29,020 --> 00:05:32,699
So if productivity collapses, who pays the bill.

98
00:05:32,699 --> 00:05:34,259
The research is very clear.

99
00:05:34,300 --> 00:05:38,899
A 3.4% decrease in labor productivity

100
00:05:38,899 --> 00:05:42,860
corresponds almost perfectly to a reduction of 3.3%

101
00:05:42,860 --> 00:05:45,180
in total hourly compensation.

102
00:05:45,180 --> 00:05:47,579
The rules of economics offer no discounts.

103
00:05:47,579 --> 00:05:50,219
If the entire machinery becomes less efficient,

104
00:05:50,219 --> 00:05:55,219
the only way the system adapts is by lowering the wages of those within it.

105
00:05:55,219 --> 00:05:59,860
And this graph brilliantly demonstrates how widespread the problem is.

106
00:05:59,939 --> 00:06:00,939
Pay attention here,

107
00:06:00,939 --> 00:06:04,780
because aging doesn't just hit the paychecks of the elderly.

108
00:06:04,780 --> 00:06:09,780
Sure, we see a 3.4% drop in wage growth for the over-60s.

109
00:06:09,780 --> 00:06:11,020
But look at the rest,

110
00:06:11,020 --> 00:06:16,020
there is a 2.9% drop for the middle age group of 40-59 years old

111
00:06:16,020 --> 00:06:20,699
and even a 1.7% decrease for young people between 20 and 39.

112
00:06:20,699 --> 00:06:22,819
Aging penalizes everyone.

113
00:06:22,819 --> 00:06:26,900
Fewer elderly people at work probably means fewer positive spillovers,

114
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:29,580
like innovation, the transfer of skills,

115
00:06:29,620 --> 00:06:34,139
or that vitality essential for wage growth across all generations.

116
00:06:34,139 --> 00:06:37,459
We come to the final section, number 6,

117
00:06:37,459 --> 00:06:39,419
prospects for the future.

118
00:06:39,419 --> 00:06:40,740
What awaits us?

119
00:06:40,740 --> 00:06:44,259
If we apply the calculations of this research to the near future,

120
00:06:44,259 --> 00:06:46,740
the projections are hair-raising,

121
00:06:46,740 --> 00:06:51,060
between 2020 and 2030, the share of the elderly population

122
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:54,699
is set to grow by another 11%.

123
00:06:54,699 --> 00:06:58,579
Doing the math, this could mean an annual loss of growth

124
00:06:58,579 --> 00:07:00,539
of 0.6%.

125
00:07:00,539 --> 00:07:04,620
It means we are literally doubling the braking effect on GDP

126
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:06,419
that we experienced in the past.

127
00:07:06,419 --> 00:07:09,539
And before anyone thinks that simply buying new machinery

128
00:07:09,539 --> 00:07:12,339
is enough to solve the problem, the data warns us.

129
00:07:12,339 --> 00:07:14,779
The increase in physical capital investment

130
00:07:14,779 --> 00:07:17,659
offers only very, very limited support

131
00:07:17,659 --> 00:07:19,979
against this structural decline.

132
00:07:19,979 --> 00:07:22,419
Which brings us to the final question,

133
00:07:22,419 --> 00:07:24,979
the real challenge of our time.

134
00:07:24,979 --> 00:07:27,819
Will automation, artificial intelligence

135
00:07:27,860 --> 00:07:30,819
and new technologies be able to increase

136
00:07:30,819 --> 00:07:33,500
our productivity to such an extreme extent

137
00:07:33,500 --> 00:07:36,899
as to compensate for this inexorable demographic decline?

138
00:07:36,899 --> 00:07:39,819
If technology cannot achieve this miracle,

139
00:07:39,819 --> 00:07:44,819
demographic weight will continue to heavily slow down the global economy for decades.

140
00:07:44,819 --> 00:07:48,980
It is a massive question, and it will be fascinating, albeit worrying,

141
00:07:48,980 --> 00:07:51,459
to discover the answer in the coming years.